## Loki Logging Standards

Every new piece of code that handles an external input or produces an output MUST emit
at least one structured log entry. This is a hard requirement — not optional.

### Coverage requirements (mandatory for any new code)

- **Every new action handler**: call `_logger.Structured()` for `action_dispatched` on entry
  and `action_result` on exit with `success`, `duration_ms`, `correlation_id`. Plain `_logger.Info()`
  at action boundaries is not acceptable.
- **Every new WebSocket message type in DashboardBridge**: log `action_received` on entry
  with a freshly generated `correlation_id`.
- **Every new iRacing broadcast or SDK call path**: log the dispatch event and its outcome.
- **Every new incident detection path**: emit `incident_detected` with full identifying fields.
- **Every new lifecycle hook** (Init, End, SDK callbacks): log a named lifecycle event.

### What must NEVER be logged

- **Per-tick state**: never call `_logger` (or `Structured`) inside `DataUpdate()` except via
  an explicit throttle guard (minimum 10 s between identical messages — see `WaitingLogThrottleMs`).
  Any new tick-level log call without a throttle guard will be rejected.
- **Full state blobs**: never serialize `PluginSnapshot`, `SessionSummary`, or raw YAML into
  a log line. Log identifiers and counts only.
- **Loki sink errors into Loki**: `LokiSink` failures write to the local file log only —
  never re-enqueue to avoid a feedback loop.

### Line size budget

Self-imposed ceiling: **8 KB per log line** (Grafana Cloud hard limit is 256 KB, non-modifiable).
Typical lines should be under 800 bytes. Trim fields if a line would exceed 8 KB.

### Volume guard

Even 1 log per DataUpdate tick = 86 MB/hour. Target: < 1 MB per race session.
Any new log path that could fire more than once per second MUST have a documented
throttle guard in the PR/commit description.

### Event and label reference

See `docs/GRAFANA-LOGGING.md` for the full event taxonomy, label schema, and LogQL query patterns.

## Development Cadence

- **Small changes only.** Each task should touch the minimum number of files needed.
  Prefer one logical change per editing session — one new class, one modified method,
  one config file. Large sweeping changes hide bugs and make rollback hard.
- **Check after every change.** After each edit: run `dotnet build` (0 errors required),
  run `ReadLints` on changed files (0 new errors), and if the change touches runtime
  behaviour, do a quick deploy-and-test cycle before moving to the next task.
- **Commit at milestones.** A milestone is any point where the build is green, tests pass,
  and the change is independently useful or safe to ship (e.g. "LokiSink compiles and
  no-ops when unconfigured", "all action handlers emit structured logs", "local stack
  confirmed pushing data"). Do not accumulate multiple milestones in one commit.
  All executed plans and agent commands that change the repo must be established in a
  commit (see [commit-after-execution](.cursor/rules/commit-after-execution.mdc)).
- **One todo at a time.** Mark a todo `in_progress` before starting it. Do not start the
  next todo until the current one is committed and green.
- **Retry-once-then-stop rule still applies.** If a build or test fails after one fix
  attempt, hard stop — do not keep iterating blindly.
